<div id="content" lang="en" dir="ltr">
This page contains <em><strong>SPOILERS</strong></em> <hr>
 <a class="nonexistent" href="./XandorTikroth">XandorTikroth</a>: Okay, so I'm thinking about kicking around a Mimic. 
    <ul>

 <strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: Well, first you place the Mimic on the ground in front of you, and then you pull back your foot, take careful aim, and.... ;-) 
    </ul>


<p>
The only problem is that the Spoiler page for Mimics hasn't been created, and I know next to nothing about Mimics.  So, has anyone extensively played a Mimic Character?  Know any good races?  Race Modifiers?  At what levels do you get stuff?  That kind of thing...  Anyway, thanks in advance for the help! 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: I haven't played one myself. Only one or two of my Loremasters ever put points into it, and I never put enough points into it to be able to tell you anything useful. 
</p>
<p>
You can always look at the <a class="external" href="./angband.oook.cz/ladder-browse.php?v=ToME&amp;r=&amp;c=Mimic&amp;n=&amp;e=&amp;s=0"><img src="./wiki/starshine/img/moin-www.png" alt="[WWW]" height="11" width="11">ToME Mimic ladder on oook</a> for ideas and read the comments there. They appear to be a difficult class. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./SoulWynd">SoulWynd</a></strong>: They can be very easy if you play a <a class="nonexistent" href="./DeathMold">DeathMold</a> and get more necromancy. The mix mimicry+symbiosis is a good one too. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a class="nonexistent" href="./XandorTikroth">XandorTikroth</a></strong>: @Maylith: Man, that comment nearly knocked me out of my seat, lol! 
</p>
<p>
@<a href="./SoulWynd">SoulWynd</a>: So, if I'm reading you right, you start up a Deathmold Mimic, and immediately start mimicing using the Wolf Pelt, right?  So, every time you drop out of that, you re-mimic, correct?  So, then, what happens to the Deathmold's attributes and such?  I'm assuming that I'd lose the intrinsic Deathmold powers, but what about the stats? 
</p>
<p>
I'll definitely try it.  Thanks for the help. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: Sorry, I simply couldn't resist such a good straight line. :D 
</p>
<p>
Anyway, one thing I would caution you on, Xandor, is that the Deathmold is an experimental class, and on certain special dungeon levels you can run into real trouble with Deathmolds unless you are very well prepared. (If anyone expands on this, please mark this thread as spoily -- not because of the class, but because of the special levels.) 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./ZasVid">ZasVid</a></strong>: Deathmolds and mimicry - mimicry grants power to grow legs and (i think)walk like anyone normal anytime you want (provided you have access to that spell already). And it always gives power to assume shape bound with currently worn mimicry cloak, so no more annoying movement! However, Deathmold racial powers are lost, but stats &amp; skill boni remain (though stats become slightly different due to pluses or minuses of every shape). If you want more specific information, you may want to see <a class="interwiki" title="Self" href="./Spoilers_2fMagic_2fMimicry"><img src="./wiki/starshine/img/moin-inter.png" alt="[Self]" height="16" width="16">this spoiler</a> describing abilities of every shape possible. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a class="nonexistent" href="./XandorTikroth">XandorTikroth</a></strong>: Well, it says there that the Eagle cloak thing only lasts for a duration of 10-50 turns.  Well, with a Hobbit Swordmaster that I'm running (with only 15 or so points dumped into Mimicry) the Eagle Mimic lasts for several hundred turns, at least as far as I can tell.  It lasted me through several tries for a FF quest for 18 Master Liches in Mordor...  So what gives? 
</p>

    <ul>

 <strong><a href="./ZasVid">ZasVid</a></strong>: Not the cloak. The morphic oil of eagle lasts 10-50 turns. When using mimic cloaks you get additional duration of 20 turns per Mimicry skill level (in 2.2.x). On top of that, I suppose its 20 'normal' turns, so if you're faster than normal you get even more duration. 
    </ul>


<p>
I will try Deathmolds, though, they look interesting, especially if I'm able to not only get up and move, but also retain those awesome boni to STR and CON, plus those outrageous hit die! 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: Once enough information gets collected, this page could be the basis for the beginning of Spoilers/Classes/Mimic... 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./SoulWynd">SoulWynd</a></strong>: Actually, in my experience, the mouse form is the best for the Death Mold until you start wearing 4 rings of speed. ;) ... I play a lot with mimics, I think they're quite fun and you get enough points for weaponmastery 50 + maxblows 1 and 2 + spread of blows + another skill almost maxed. The advantage of using a death mold mimic is that you have the best of the two worlds, being able to turn your death mold powers on and off at will. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: What version of ToME are you playing, SoulWynd? Rat mimicry isn't available in 2.2.7, just Mouse, Ent, Wolf, Eagle, and Spider. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./SoulWynd">SoulWynd</a></strong>: CVS and I'm sorry, I meant to say mouse. The advantage of mouse is that it gains absurd quantities of stealth and speed as you increase your mimicry. With starting stealth and mouse form at level 20 you can get legendary stealth easily while still using running movement. The cloak of mist (if I remember the name correctly) is also great but it's another 2.3 form. 
</p>
